  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 고려왕부 단사관(高麗王府斷事官) : '
    value: 고려 충선왕(忠宣王)이 무슨 일로 원나라 정부에 미움을 사서 토번(지금의 서장 근처)으로 귀양 가게 되었으므로, 잠시 섭정격인 단사관을 원나라에서 두었던 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 필삭(筆削) : '
    value: 필주(筆誅)라는 말과 같은 뜻이다. 죄 있는 자를 실제로 죽일 권한이 없는 사람으로서 그 죄상을 명백하게 기록하여 세상에 발표하는 것을 말하는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 주(周)나라의……붙이랴 : '
    value: 당나라 고종황제의 황후인 무측천(武則天)이란 여자가 고종을 독살하고 자기가 정권을 잡아, 당나라의 나라 이름까지 고쳐서 주(周)라고 한 것이 22년간이었다. 그것을 송나라의 사마광(司馬光)이 《자치통감》을 편찬할 때 정식 황제로 대우하였으나 여기에서는 그것이 부당하다고 한 말이다. 그 후에 주자가 《통감강목》을 편찬할 때에는 그 무측천을 당나라의 역적으로 지적하였다.
english:
  title: Epitaph of Lord Lee of Gyerim, Posthumously Titled Lord of Loyal Devotion
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the twenty-seventh year of the Zhizheng era, in the seventh month of the year of Ding-wei, with autumn upon us, there passed from this world at his residence a man of true sincerity and exemplary integrity, a contributor to harmony and blessings, a pillar of three Kims upon the heights—the Lord of Gyerim, keeper of the Archives of Arts and Letters, Master Lee of the Pleasant Study. He had reached the age of eighty-one. The Court of Rites bestowed upon him the posthumous name of Loyal Devotion.

    In the tenth month, his funeral cortege assembled with proper ceremonies, and he was laid to rest in the ancestral tomb of Dori Village in Ufeng County. In the winter of the year Bing-chen, his spirit was enshrined in the temple of the late king.

    The Master's given name was Qi-xian, his courtesy name Zhong-si. His family was the house of Lee. From the founding of Silla by the heroic ancestor Hyeokgeose came great ministers of state, among them Lee Alp'yong. Through the ages the line continued—from Administrator Su-ban and his son Geomyeong, who fathered Military Commander Kim Hyun, who fathered Defender of Three Kingdoms Kim Seo. When King Kim Bu of Silla yielded his realm to the court of the north and took the hand of Princess Nakhrang, daughter of the founding king, a daughter was born to wed Kim Seo. Thus was born Yunhong, and from Yunhong came Seunggun, and from him Zhou-bok, and from him Cheng, and from him Chilian, and from him Chongseom, and from him Chunjong, and from him Hyunbok, and from him Sunyong, and from him Seunggao.

    Seunggao fathered a court official named Dukgyeon, whose son was the late Vice Minister Hyuk, who in turn fathered Minister Jinbaek, styled Man of Letters. This minister took as his wife a woman of the Pak family from the house of Daelung, producing our Master in the twelfth month of the year Ding-hai in the era of Zhiyuan, on the day Geng-chen.

    From childhood the Master bore himself with the dignity of a grown man. When learning to compose, he already possessed the bearing of a true writer. In the year Xinchhou of the era Dade, at fifteen years of age, when the Imperial Examiner of Rites held the examination at the National Academy, all the candidates displayed their abilities and boasted of their talents—until they heard the Master's composition. Then their spirits fell, their confidence shattered, and none dared contest for first place. And indeed, the Master took first. That same year, when Kwon Pu of the Gujai study and Zhao Jian of the Yuexuan study conducted the examination, the Master placed again among the upper ranks. Kwon Pu then gave his daughter as the Master's wife. But the Master said: "This is but a small skill, insufficient to greatly cultivate one's virtue. I must study the great classics and penetrate their depths, comparing and correcting until I reach the truth." Hearing this, Minister Jinbaek rejoiced greatly, saying: "Perhaps Heaven intends to magnify our house."

    In the year Guimao he served as keeper of the royal storehouse and clerk of the Yanjing Palace. In Wushen he was selected into the Archives of Arts and Letters, where all the scholars yielded place to him and dared not discuss matters of composition. Later he was transferred as instructor to Jie-an prefecture, then elevated to censor. In Gengxu he became assistant of the Ministry of Personnel. In Xinhai he rose twice more, becoming vice-director of the Imperial Examination Bureau and inspector of the Three Ministries. In all positions he acquitted himself well.

    In the year Renzi of the era Huangqing, he was appointed investigating commissioner for the western maritime provinces, bearing the ancient authority of those who wielded the rod of office. He rose to education officer of the National Academy, and in winter took charge of the imperial grain repositories. In the year Guichou he became deputy minister of those repositories, overseeing weights and measures. The Master executed these duties without hesitation, and people said: "Truly, Lord Lee is the sort of man who can turn his hand to anything."

    King Zhongxuan had secured the throne for the young emperor and earned the favor of the Mongol court beyond measure. He then requested that the realm pass to King Zhongsu, taking himself the title of Grand Commandant and dwelling in the capital of the Yuan, where he built a Hall of Ten Thousand Volumes to study and content himself. He said: "All the finest scholars of Yuan's capital come to my house, yet I have no man of letters worthy of the name. This is my shame." And so he summoned the Master to the capital—in the first month of the year Jiaxin of the era Yanyou. There Yao Muanm, Yan Zijing, Yuan Fuchu, and Zhao Ziang all graced the king's circle. The Master moved among these luminaries, and his learning advanced greatly. All the great men praised him without ceasing.

    In the year Yimao he was promoted to secretary of the Ministry of Personnel, and in autumn appointed vice-director of the National Academy, retaining his secretarial office. In Bingchen he was sent on mission to western Shu, and everywhere he passed his verses were recited and celebrated. That year he became judge of the Imperial Examination Bureau. In Dingsi he was promoted to vice-minister of Personnel. In Jiwei, when the king made a journey to south of the Yangtze, beholding the towers and pavilions and scenic beauty, moved by the landscape to compose poetry, he said more than once: "This place is not fitting without Li-sheng." In Gengqin he was appointed to oversee the Privy Council and received the honorific Upright and Loyal Contributor to Harmony. He took charge of examinations and was praised for discovering worthy men. He was then but thirty-four years of age.

    When Minister Jinbaek, the Tartar lady, his maternal grandfather, and the three examination officials were all in health, the Master raised a cup and offered toasts to their long life. All the world admired and envied him. That year he received appointment as judicial officer of the Korean Royal Household. In winter of the year Renxu of the era Zhizhi he returned to the capital. But before he arrived, King Zhongxuan fell victim to slanders and was exiled to the western regions. The next year the Master journeyed to see him, and along the way his verses brimmed with loyalty and righteous indignation.

    In the year Jiazi of the era Taiding, he was elevated to Grand Master of Rectitude and appointed to the Privy Council. In Yichou his honorific was changed to True-hearted and Upright. He rose twice more to become judge and drafter of imperial documents. In Bingyin he moved to become minister of the Three Departments. In the year Gengwu of the era Tiandli, when King Zhonghui took power, the Master again became drafter of documents, but soon was dismissed.

    It was in the year Bingzi of the era Zhihou that he was enfeoffed as Lord of Gimhae and appointed keeper of the Archives of Arts and Letters. In the second month of the year Guimao, King Zhongsu passed away. That autumn, Minister Cao Qi usurped authority, stationed soldiers at the Yongan Palace, and declared he would remove wicked men from the throne. But secretly he plotted for the Prince of Shen. King Zhonghui led his cavalry and struck him down. Yet his conspirators remained many in the capital, and all sought to implicate the king in wrongdoing. The people lived in fear and doubt, and great calamity seemed imminent. The Master, filled with righteous fury, disregarding his own safety, declared: "I know but the son of my sovereign," and followed the king to the capital. There, speaking through the written word, he clarified matters and vindicated the throne. His service was of the first order.

    When he returned, lesser men grew bold in their slanders. The Master withdrew from public view and composed his Ramblings of the Oak-leaf Hermit. In winter of the year Jiashen of the era Zhizheng, when King Zhongmok ascended, the Master was elevated to Lord of the Manor and appointed keeper of the Shrine of Filial Piety. He became teacher to the royal heir. In the year Bingxu he edited the Records of King Zhongyeol. In Wengzi he became minister of the Three Departments. In winter of the year Xinmao, when the present king assumed the throne, the Master, though not yet in his own realm, was appointed right prime minister with provisional charge of the Eastern Conquest Province. For several months the state lay in confusion, yet through the Master's wise measures the people found peace and stability. In the year Renchen he was given the great honorific Upright, Loyal, and Harmonious. But Zhao Rilsin, an original follower of the king, envied that the Master's rank exceeded his own. When the Master learned this, he thrice submitted memorials requesting to be relieved of the honor. That autumn, Zhao Rilsin gathered malcontents and by night invaded the palace, slaughtering those he disliked and casting the realm into chaos. But the Master, having already retired, escaped the disaster. When Rilsin was later captured and executed, the Master was recalled as right prime minister.

    In the year Guisi he resigned in the first month. In the fifth month he was appointed Lord of the Manor and took charge of examinations. In the year Jiawu, in the twelfth month, he was made right prime minister once more. He resigned again the following year, when he had reached seventy. He was enfeoffed as Lord of Gimhae in the twelfth month and appointed to the rank of Left Prime Minister. In the fifth month of the year Dingyi, he petitioned to retire on full stipend. The throne granted his wish. Yet by the nation's law, a retired lord retains stipends greater than common officials. The Master, uncomfortable with this arrangement, sought to retire without rank. The court, however, held that such retirement would not properly honor a great minister, and in the year Renyin he was again made Lord of Gyerim.

    The Master, from his passing of the examinations at fifteen, had held a name that eclipsed his generation. From his first appointment at court, he devoted himself wholly to matters of state and writing, serving in the Archives from subordinate posts to the highest ranks of Lord of the Manor, never leaving his duties save during the three years of King Zhongjeong's reign, when he was absent because he had memorialized the throne to establish the present king.

    The Master's nature was grave and deep, refined through broad learning. His counsel was just and his deeds luminous. When he read the Records, he took his principles of revision from the Spring and Autumn Annals. Reaching the reign of the Empress Wu, he noted: "Should we weave the remnants of Zhou into the history of our Tang?" Later, finding Zhu Xi's Outline and Digest of the Comprehensive Mirror, he verified that his judgment had been correct. Of any man's small virtue, he spoke in praise, fearing lest good deed go unheard. Of the deeds of former worthies, however small, he said they were difficult to equal. In his long life he never spoke harshly or bore a solemn countenance, nor did he indulge in vulgar speech. Receiving guests over wine, he would discuss and examine the affairs of ancient and modern times without tiring. The elder Cui Zhuole marveled: "Men say that strangers after three days' parting must look anew upon each other. I have seen this truth in Master Yi-jae." The Master sought always to follow the ancient way and was loath to make sudden changes. He would say: "My will is not inferior to that of ancients, but my talents fall short of modern men."

    The Master's grandson had taken a wife from the Qi family. The Master, fearing their excessive prominence, was troubled when they rose to high office. When the grandson was appointed chancellor, the king commanded the court to compose verses in celebration and asked the Master to compose a narrative of the event. But the Master declined. He took the name Yi-jae, the Master of the Pleasant Study. When Shin Don fell from power, the king said: "The Master's prescience is beyond compare. He once said that Shin Don was not an honest man, and lo, it has proven true." From his youth, the Master's peers dared not call him by name, but always said "Yi-jae," and when he became chancellor, all men, high and low alike, called him Yi-jae. Thus was he honored in his time.

    The Master compiled numerous volumes of writings that circulate in the world. He was married three times. His first wife, Lady Kwon of Gilchang, bore him two sons and three daughters. The eldest son, Seo-jong, served as grand sacrificer and deputy minister of the Ancestral Temple. The second, Dal-jon, was grand sacrificer, inspector of works, and controller of the archives. His eldest daughter married Lord Rim Deok-su, judge of the Palace Guard. His second married Lord Lee Gye-son, controller of agriculture. His third married Lord Kim Hui-jo, chancellor of the Hanlin Academy, and was enfeoffed as lady of the Yi-hwa estate.

    His second wife, Lady Pak of Suchun, daughter of the sub-commissioner of the Myriad Households of the Western Capital, bore him one son and three daughters. The son, Chang-ro, became prefect of Kaesong. His daughters married Lord Pak Dong-saeng, judge of agriculture; Lord Song Muo, judge of examinations; and became the nun Hye-bi.

    His third wife, Lady So of Seo-won, daughter of the magistrate of Seo-ju, bore him two daughters. They married Lord Kim Nam-u, minister of the Three Departments, and Lord Lee Yu-bang, vice-physician.

    Through secondary unions, two more daughters were born, one marrying General Lim Bu-yang, the other yet young.

    His eldest son Jonbu married the daughter of the Privy Counselor Hong Yu and had one son, Bo-rim, who became lecturer, then rose through the ranks to great general. His daughters married Lord Cho Mu, judge of propriety, and Lord Lee Won-chok, prefect of Shun-hung.

    Daljon married the daughter of General Kim Song-ju and had a son named Nae-yu, who became abbot of the Gwangdo Monastery.

    The inspector of works married the daughter of Lord Baek Yi-jong and had three sons: Deok-rim, who became magistrate of Yi-hung; Su-rim, who served as counselor and later as Hanlin scholar under Yuan, bringing honors to the Master; and Hak-rim, who became minor prefect. His daughter married General Ki In-gyol.

    The prefect of Kaesong married the daughter of Lord Kim Kong-ui and had one daughter marrying Inspector Won Su.

    The judge of agriculture married the daughter of Minister Kim Myong and had two sons and one daughter.

    The other children and grandchildren married into various households, each establishing their own lines, numbering many in all.

    Thereupon was composed this epitaph:

    *Heaven and earth store up their essence,
    And the Master was born of it.
    The stars of the scholars' chamber shone with light,
    And the Master revealed it.
    His fame spread throughout all lands,
    Yet his body dwelt in the Eastern sea.
    First among the virtuous,
    Chief among the literary.
    As the Pleiades and the Northern Star,
    As the great mountain peaks,
    As the radiant wind and clear moon,
    So was he.
    Four times he held the reins of state,
    Eighty winters passed his brow.
    The blessing of the unicorn and phoenix,
    The wisdom of the sage and tortoise—
    His merit upheld the realm,
    His grace flowed to the people.
    In the hall of ancestors he sits enshrined,
    With sorrow and honor without equal.
    You his children and grandchildren,
    Follow his loyalty and filial devotion.
    Think not that he has faded,
    For the Master dwells in the nines below.*
